[{"id":40744,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["$0.001$","$0.002$","$0.0005$","$0.0025$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & 300 \\mathrm{msd}=15 \\mathrm{~cm} \\\\ & 1 \\mathrm{msd}=\\frac{15}{300} \\mathrm{~cm}=0.05 \\mathrm{~cm} \\\\ & 25 \\mathrm{vsd}=24 \\mathrm{msd} \\\\ & 1 \\mathrm{vsd}=\\frac{24}{25} \\mathrm{msd} \\\\ & \\mathrm{LC}=1 \\mathrm{msd}-1 \\mathrm{vsd}\\end{aligned}$<br/>$\\begin{aligned}<br/>& \\mathrm{LC}=1 \\mathrm{msd}-\\frac{24}{25} \\mathrm{msd}=\\frac{1}{25} \\mathrm{msd} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{LC}=\\frac{1}{25} \\times 0.05=0.002 \\mathrm{~cm}<br/>\\end{aligned}$<br/>correct option (2)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40751,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["$2.0 \\mathrm{~g} / \\mathrm{cm}^3$","$1.7 \\mathrm{~g} / \\mathrm{cm}^3$","$2.2 \\mathrm{~g} / \\mathrm{cm}^3$","$2.5 \\mathrm{~g} / \\mathrm{cm}^3$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Given $9 \\mathrm{MSD}=10 \\mathrm{VSD}$\n$\\operatorname{mass}=8.635 \\mathrm{~g}$\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{LC}=1 \\mathrm{MSD}-1 \\mathrm{VSD} \\\\ & \\mathrm{LC}=1 \\mathrm{MSD}-\\frac{9}{10} \\mathrm{MSD} \\\\ & \\mathrm{LC}=\\frac{1}{10} \\mathrm{MSD} \\\\ & \\mathrm{LC}=0.01 \\mathrm{~cm}\\end{aligned}$\nReading of diameter $=\\mathrm{MSR}+\\mathrm{LC} \\times \\mathrm{VSR}$\n$\\begin{aligned} & =2 \\mathrm{~cm}+(0.01) \\times(2) \\\\ & =2.02 \\mathrm{~cm}\\end{aligned}$\nVolume of sphere $=\\frac{4}{3} \\pi\\left(\\frac{d}{2}\\right)^3=\\frac{4}{3} \\pi\\left(\\frac{2.02}{2}\\right)^3$\n$=4.32 \\mathrm{~cm}^3$\nDensity $=\\frac{\\text { mass }}{\\text { volume }}=\\frac{8.635}{4.32}=1.998 \\sim 2.00 \\mathrm{~g}$<br />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40793,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["<math><mn>5.755</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","<math><mn>5.740</mn><mi> </mi><mi>m</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","<math><mn>5.725</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","<math><mn>5.950</mn><mi> </mi><mi>m</mi><mi>m</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>least count <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0.5</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0.005</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>m</mi></math><br /><br />Reading <math><mo>=</mo><mn>5.5</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>m</mi><mo>+</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>48</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0.005</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>m</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mn>5.725</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>m</mi><mo>.</mo></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40769,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Vernier constant is the least count of the vernier&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>C</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>zero error <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math>correction<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>.</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>.</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>.</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>The diameter of the sphere will be,</p><p>diameter<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>MSR</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>VSR</mi><mo>+</mo></math>correction</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>180</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40745,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/rAna8MLZ-gX6N34QrstoaoaKsJgIUdnv9Qso9k19sDM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\nSince least count of the instrument can be calculated as\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\text { Least count }=\\frac{\\text { pitch length }}{\\text { No. of division on circular scale }} \\\\\n& =\\frac{0.75}{15}=0.05 \\mathrm{~mm} .\n\\end{aligned}$\n\nHere we are provided $\\mathrm{L}=5 \\mathrm{~mm} \\& \\mathrm{~W}=2.5 \\mathrm{~mm}$ $\\mathrm{L}=5 \\mathrm{~mm} \\& \\mathrm{~W}=2.5 \\mathrm{~mm}$\n$\\because$ We know that\n$\\mathrm{A}=\\mathrm{L} . \\mathrm{W}$\nFor calculating fractional error, we can write\n$\\frac{\\mathrm{dA}}{\\mathrm{~A}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{dL}}{\\mathrm{~L}}+\\frac{\\mathrm{dW}}{\\mathrm{~W}}$\n\nHere $\\mathrm{dL}=\\mathrm{dW}=0.05 \\mathrm{~mm}$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\frac{\\mathrm{dA}}{\\mathrm{~A}}=\\frac{0.05}{5}+\\frac{0.05}{2.5} \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow \\frac{\\mathrm{dA}}{\\mathrm{~A}}=\\frac{1}{100}+\\frac{2}{100}=\\frac{3}{100}\n\\end{aligned}$\n\nSo, $x=3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40803,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["$0.052 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$0.026 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$0.005 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$0.52 \\mathrm{~cm}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Diameter of wire $=\\frac{1}{100} \\times 52=0.52 \\mathrm{~mm}=0.052 \\mathrm{~cm}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":40785,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["<math><mn>384</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>332</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>338</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>379</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Speed of sound, <math><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>f</mi><mtext> </mtext><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></math>  <br/><math><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>480</mn><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>0.70</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0.30</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>  <br/><math><mo>=</mo><mn>384</mn><mtext> </mtext><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mo>/</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow></mrow></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40773,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>M</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>V</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>V</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>M</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>L</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>C</mi><mo>.</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>M</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>V</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>M</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></math><br />Reading <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math> Main scale reading <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo></math> L.C. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#215;</mo></math> vernier scale reading<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>+</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math></p><p>Reading of diameter<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math><br />radius of the bob<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>52</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>52</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40740,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["0.001","0.1","0.01","0.05"],"answer":2,"solution":"Least count is the smallest division readable on an instrument scale.<br>Given readings are 1.24 mm, 1.25 mm, 1.23 mm, 1.21 mm, all expressed to two decimal places.<br>The precision of measurement shows differences as small as 0.01 mm (e.g., 1.25 - 1.24 = 0.01 mm).<br>This indicates all readings can be recorded to the nearest 0.01 mm, which represents the smallest measurable division.<br>Therefore, the least count of the instrument is 0.01 mm.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40749,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["$(2 \\mathrm{~N}-1)$","$\\left(\\frac{2 \\mathrm{~N}-1}{2 \\mathrm{~N}}\\right)$","$\\left(\\frac{2 \\mathrm{~N}-1}{2}\\right)$","$\\left(\\frac{2 \\mathrm{~N}-1}{20 \\mathrm{~N}}\\right)$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Least count of vernier calipers $=\\frac{1}{20 \\mathrm{~N}} \\mathrm{~cm}$\n$\\because$ Least count $=1 \\mathrm{MSD}-1 \\mathrm{VSD}$\nlet $\\mathrm{x}$ no. of divisions of main scale coincides with $\\mathrm{N}$ division of vernier scale, then\n$\\begin{aligned} & 1 \\mathrm{VSD}=\\frac{\\mathrm{x} \\times 1 \\mathrm{~mm}}{\\mathrm{~N}} \\\\ & \\therefore \\frac{1}{20 \\mathrm{~N}} \\mathrm{~cm}=1 \\mathrm{~mm}-\\frac{\\mathrm{x} \\times 1 \\mathrm{~mm}}{\\mathrm{~N}} \\\\ & \\frac{1}{2 \\mathrm{~N}} \\mathrm{~mm}=1 \\mathrm{~mm}-\\frac{\\mathrm{x}}{\\mathrm{N}} \\mathrm{mm} \\\\ & \\mathrm{x}=\\left(1-\\frac{1}{2 \\mathrm{~N}}\\right) \\mathrm{N} \\\\ & \\mathrm{x}=\\frac{2 \\mathrm{~N}-1}{2}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40796,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["<math><mn>0.70</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>0.50</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>0.75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>0.80</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0.5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>50</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0.01</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math><br /><br />Zero error <math><mo>=</mo><mn>0.50</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0.45</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>0.05</mn></math><br /><br />Thickness <math><mo>=</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>0.5</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0.01</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>0.05</mn></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0.50</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0.25</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0.05</mn></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0.80</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (03 Apr)","image":null},{"id":40759,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["Radius of curvature of concave surface","Specific rotation of liquids","Thickness of thin plates","Radius of curvature of convex surface"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>A spherometer is a device used for measuring the curvature of surfaces, particularly the radius of curvature of spherical or cylindrical surfaces. It consists of a central leg with a fine screw, and three outer legs that form a tripod. The device is primarily designed for measuring dimensions related to curved surfaces.</p><p>Specific rotation is a property related to the rotation of plane-polarized light in a substance. It is not measured using a spherometer. Instead, a polarimeter is typically used to measure specific rotation.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40777,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>36</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>54</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>58</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>56</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Positive zero error <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math></p><p>Main scale reading <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>Vernier scale reading<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>06</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>Final reading<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>06</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>54</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40738,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["$1 \\times 10^{-2}$","$1 \\times 10^{-3}$","$5 \\times 10^{-2}$","$5 \\times 10^{-3}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Pitch of the screw gauge is the linear distance moved in one complete rotation.<br><br>$\\text{Pitch} = \\dfrac{2.5}{5} = 0.5 \\text{ mm}$<br><br>Least count of the screw gauge is given by the ratio of the pitch to the total number of divisions on the circular scale.<br><br>$\\text{Least count} = \\dfrac{\\text{Pitch}}{\\text{Number of divisions on circular scale}}$<br><br>$\\text{Least count} = \\dfrac{0.5}{100} = 0.005 \\text{ mm}$<br><br>$\\text{Least count} = 5 \\times 10^{-3} \\text{ mm}$<br><br>Answer: $5 \\times 10^{-3}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40790,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["$20 \\Omega$","$40 \\Omega$","$60 \\Omega$","$30 \\Omega$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Initially at null deflection $\\frac{\\mathrm{R}_{1}}{\\mathrm{R}_{2}}=\\frac{2}{3}$$\\ldots(\\mathrm{i})$\r\n\r\nFinally at null deflection, when null point is shifted $\\frac{\\mathrm{R}_{1}+10}{\\mathrm{R}_{2}}=1 \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{R}_{1}+10=\\mathrm{R}_{2}$...(ii)\r\n\r\nSolving equations (i) and (ii) we get $\\frac{2 R_{2}}{3}+10=R_{2}$\r\n\r\n$10=\\frac{\\mathrm{R}_{2}}{3} \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{R}_{2}=30 \\Omega$\r\n\r\n$\\& R_{1}=20 \\Omega$\r\n\r\nNow if required resistance is $\\mathrm{R}$ then $\\frac{\\frac{30 \\times \\mathrm{R}}{30+\\mathrm{R}}}{30}=\\frac{2}{3}$\r\n\r\n$\\mathrm{R}=60 \\Omega$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40757,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo> </mo><mi>mm</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The number of divisions on the vernier scale <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn></math></p><p>Main scale division <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>MSD</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi>mm</mi></math></p><p>As, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn></math> divisions on the vernier scale coincide with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>49</mn></math> divisions on the main scale,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>VSD</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>49</mn><mn>50</mn></mfrac><mi>MSD</mi></math></p><p>The minimum inaccuracy in the measurement of distance by a vernier scale,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math> Least count of the vernier scale</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi>MSD</mi><mo>–</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi>VSD</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi>MSD</mi><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mn>9</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>MSD</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>5</mn><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>MSD</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>50</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>0</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi>mm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo> </mo><mi>mm</mi></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40791,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["$0.4 \\mathrm{~V}$","$0.3 \\mathrm{~V}$","$0.6 \\mathrm{~V}$","$0.5 \\mathrm{~V}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Given, Emf of cell, $\\varepsilon=0.5 \\mathrm{v}$ Rheostat resistance, $\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{h}}=2 \\Omega$ Potential gradient is\r\n\r\n$\\frac{d v}{d L}=\\left(\\frac{6}{2+4}\\right) \\times \\frac{4}{L}$\r\n\r\nLet null point be at $\\ell \\mathrm{cm}$ when cell of $\\mathrm{emf} \\varepsilon=0.5 \\mathrm{v}$ is used.\r\n\r\nthus $\\varepsilon_{1}=0.5 \\mathrm{~V}=\\left(\\frac{6}{2+4}\\right) \\times \\frac{4}{\\mathrm{~L}} \\times \\ell$...(i)\r\n\r\nFor resistance $\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{h}}=6 \\Omega$ new potential gradient is $\\left(\\frac{6}{4+6}\\right) \\times \\frac{4}{L}$ and at null point\r\n\r\n$\\left(\\frac{6}{4+6}\\right)\\left(\\frac{4}{\\mathrm{~L}}\\right) \\times \\ell=\\varepsilon_{2}$...(ii)\r\n\r\nDividing equation (i) by (ii) we get\r\n\r\n$\\frac{0.5}{\\varepsilon_{2}}=\\frac{10}{6}$ thus $\\varepsilon_{2}=0.3 \\mathrm{v}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40772,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Vernier constant is defined as the difference between the value of one main scale division and one vernier scale division. It is also known as the least count of vernier calliper.</p><p>The main scale division of the given vernier calliper is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>M</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></mrow><mn>20</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mi>C</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>M</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></mrow><mn>10</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40792,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>L</mi></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>11</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>24</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>L</mi></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>11</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>L</mi></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>13</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>24</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>L</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Potential difference across <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AJ</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi>J</mi></mrow></msub></math>,<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>&#949;</mi><mrow><mn>13</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#183;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>12</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow><mi>L</mi></mfrac><mo>&#183;</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br />For no current in galvanometer,<br /><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#949;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo></math> potential difference across <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AJ</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#949;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>12</mn><mi>&#949;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>13</mn><mi>L</mi></mrow></mfrac><mi>x</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>13L</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>24</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40743,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["$1.50$","$1.48$","$1.54$","$1.51$"],"answer":2,"solution":"For a screw gauge, the measurement formula is: Reading = Pitch scale + (Circular scale × Least count) - Zero error<br>The zero of circular scale lies 3 divisions above the pitch line, indicating negative zero error:<br>Zero error = -3 × 0.01 = -0.03 mm<br>Reading = 1 + (51 × 0.01) - (-0.03) = 1 + 0.51 + 0.03 = 1.54 mm","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40765,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>92</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>54</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>98</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>From the data given in the question,</p><p>Pitch of the screw gauge<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>.</p><p>Total divisions on the circular scale<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn></math>.</p><p>Therefore, the least count of the screw gauge is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>LC</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mtext>pitch</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mn>50</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math></p><p>Now,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MSR</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CSR</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn></math></p><p>Diameter reading <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MSR</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>LC</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>CSR</mi><mo>-</mo></math> zero error</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>d</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>03</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>d</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>98</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40786,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["<math><mn>1</mn></math>","<math><mn>3</mn></math>","<math><mn>2</mn></math>","<math><mn>4</mn></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"For meter bridge: <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>100</mn><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>  <br/><math><mn>1</mn><mo>→</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1000</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>60</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>40</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>⇒</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2000</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>666.67</mn><mtext> </mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></math>  <br/><math><mn>2</mn><mo>→</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>100</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>13</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>27</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>⇒</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>669.23</mn><mtext> </mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></math>  <br/><math><mn>3</mn><mo>→</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1.5</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>98.5</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>⇒</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>656.67</mn><mtext> </mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></math>  <br/><math><mn>4</mn><mo>→</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>99</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>⇒</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>99</mn><mtext> </mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></math>  <br/>Resistance calculated by using data from 4<sup>th</sup> observation is most inconsistent.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40755,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mn>11</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>50</mn><mn>11</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>11</mn></mfrac></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Given:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo> </mo><mi>M</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>11</mn><mo> </mo><mi>V</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi>V</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mn>11</mn></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi>M</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mi>C</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mi>M</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mi>V</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi>M</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mn>11</mn></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi>M</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi>M</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><mn>11</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>11</mn></mfrac></math> units</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40794,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["$0.0430 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$0.3150 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$0.4300 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$0.2150 \\mathrm{~cm}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Least count\n$$\n=\\frac{\\text { Value of } 1 \\text { part on main scale }}{\\text { Number of parts on vernier scale }}\n$$\n$$\n=\\frac{0.25}{5 \\times 100} \\mathrm{~cm}=5 \\times 10^{-4} \\mathrm{~cm}\n$$\nReading $=4 \\times 0.05 \\mathrm{~cm}+30 \\times 5 \\times 10^{-4} \\mathrm{~cm}$ $=(0.2+0.0150) \\mathrm{cm}=0.2150 \\mathrm{~cm}$ (Thickness of wire)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":40804,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["one minute","half minute","one degree","half degree"],"answer":0,"solution":"$$\n\\text { Least count }=\\frac{\\text { value of main scale division }}{\\text { No of divisions on vernier scale }}=\\frac{1}{30} \\mathrm{MSD}=\\frac{1}{30} \\times \\frac{1}{2}^{\\circ}=\\frac{1}{60}^{\\circ}=1 \\text { minute }\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":40801,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["$a$","$\\frac{a}{N}$","$\\frac{N}{N+1} \\times a$","$\\frac{a}{N+1}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"No of divisions on main scale $=N$\nNo of divisions on vernier scale $=N+1$ size of main scale division $=a$\nLet size of vernier scale division be $b$ then we have\n$$\na N=b(N+1) \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{b}=\\frac{a N}{N+1}\n$$\nLeast count is $\\mathrm{a}-\\mathrm{b}=\\mathrm{a}-\\frac{a N}{N+1}$ $=a\\left[\\frac{N+1-N}{N+1}\\right]=\\frac{a}{N+1}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (19 May Online)","image":null},{"id":40737,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["$0.07$ cm negative zero error","$0.7$ cm negative zero error","$0.07$ cm positive zero error","$0.7$ cm positive zero error"],"answer":2,"solution":"Least count of the Vernier calipers is given by $\\text{LC} = \\dfrac{1 \\text{ MSD}}{\\text{Number of VSD}}$.<br><br>Substituting the given values, $\\text{LC} = \\dfrac{1 \\text{ mm}}{10} = 0.1 \\text{ mm} = 0.01 \\text{ cm}$.<br><br>Since the zero of the Vernier scale is shifted to the right of the zero of the main scale, the zero error is positive.<br><br>The zero error is calculated as $+ (n \\times \\text{LC})$, where $n$ is the coinciding Vernier division.<br><br>Given that the $7^{\\text{th}}$ Vernier division coincides with a main scale reading, $n = 7$.<br><br>Zero error $= + (7 \\times 0.01 \\text{ cm}) = + 0.07 \\text{ cm}$.<br><br>Therefore, the Vernier caliper has a $0.07 \\text{ cm}$ positive zero error.<br><br>Answer: $0.07$ cm positive zero error","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40753,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["21","142","71","42"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{MSR}=1 \\mathrm{~mm}, \\mathrm{CSR}=42, \\text { pitch }=1 \\mathrm{~mm} \\\\ & \\mathrm{LC}=\\frac{\\text { pitch }}{\\text { No. of CSD }}=\\left(\\frac{1}{100}\\right)=0.01 \\mathrm{~mm} \\\\ & \\text { Diameter }=\\mathrm{MSR}+\\mathrm{LC} \\times \\mathrm{CSD} \\\\ & \\text { Diameter }=1+(0.01) \\times 42 \\mathrm{~mm} \\\\ & \\text { Diameter }=1.42 \\mathrm{~mm}=\\frac{\\mathrm{x}}{50} \\\\ & \\therefore \\mathrm{x}=71\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40798,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Experimental Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>87</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>91</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>81</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><msqrt><mfrac><mi>L</mi><mi>g</mi></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>L</mi></mrow><msup><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msup><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>L</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>&#960;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mi>g</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>tan&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo></math>slope of graph</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>